documents.contentPreview: When to Use Bivariate choropleth maps combine two datasets (usually numerical data) into a single map allowing us to show relatively how much of X (variable 1) and Y (variable 2) exist in each enumeration unit. documents.contentPreview: When to Use Bivariate proportional / graduated symbol maps combine two datasets (usually numerical data) into a single hybrid map symbol. documents.contentPreview: When to Use Area cartograms have enjoyed a noticeable increase in popularity in recent years and are often seen as a natural alternative to the more traditional choropleth map. documents.title: The Basics of Data Classification
documents.contentPreview: Most choropleth maps (and graduated symbol maps) employ some method of data classification. The point of classification is to take a large number of observations and group them into data ranges or classes. Why? Map readers often find a few well-defined classes are easier to understand than raw data

documents.title: Dot Density Maps
documents.contentPreview: When to Use Dot density maps are a simple yet highly effective way to show density differences in geographic distributions across a landscape. documents.contentPreview: Design in cartography can be thought of as the set of human decisions behind the map—not only the look of the map, but also choices about data, interaction, and more. documents.contentPreview: In the broadest terms, we may think of an interactive map as one that can be changed in some way by user manipulation—even spinning a globe or sticking a pin in a wall map. documents.contentPreview: Good visual hierarchy is crucial to overall effective map design. Visual hierarchy is the organization of design such that some things seem more prominent and important, and others less so. documents.contentPreview: Visual variables are “the differences in map elements as perceived by the human eye” (wiki.gis.com). No matter what the type of map, these are the fundamental ways in which graphic symbols can be distinguished. documents.title: What is a map?
documents.contentPreview: It may sound silly to ask what a map is, but it’s important to understand the what and why of maps. A simple definition is that a map is a representation of a place. documents.title: What is a web map?
documents.contentPreview: “Web map” often implies a map that is not simply on the web, but rather one that is powered by the web. A digital map is on a computer, but may not be accessible by internet, and is relatively static if it is. A web map depends on the internet. It is usually interactive and not always self-contained
